"Attention Is All You Need" is a truly monumental piece of work, a 2017 [research paper](/Academic_publishing) that fundamentally reshaped the landscape of [machine learning](/Machine_learning). Authored by a collective of eight brilliant minds at [Google](/Google), it didn't just propose an improvement; it introduced a paradigm shift with the unveiling of the [transformer](/Transformer_(machine_learning_model)) architecture. This wasn't built from scratch, mind you. It cleverly leveraged the [attention mechanism](/Attention_mechanism), a concept first elegantly articulated in 2014 by Bahdanau and his colleagues. The impact of this paper is undeniable; it's now considered a cornerstone of modern [artificial intelligence](/Artificial_intelligence), a primary catalyst for the current [AI boom](/AI_boom). The transformer's influence is pervasive, forming the backbone of countless contemporary AI systems, most notably the ubiquitous [large language models](/Large_language_model). While its initial goal was to refine [Seq2seq](/Seq2seq) techniques for the intricate task of [machine translation](/Machine_translation), the authors possessed a foresight that extended far beyond mere translation. They astutely predicted its broader applicability, envisioning its potential for tasks like [question answering](/Question_answering) and the burgeoning field of [multimodal](/Modality_(human%E2%80%93computer_interaction)) [generative AI](/Generative_AI).

The paper's authors, a formidable group including [Ashish Vaswani](/Ashish_Vaswani), [Noam Shazeer](/Noam_Shazeer), Niki Parmar, Jakob Uszkoreit, Llion Jones, [Aidan Gomez](/Aidan_Gomez), Łukasz Kaiser, and Illia Polosukhin, considered themselves "equal contributors." The order in which their names appeared was, rather amusingly, randomized, as stated within the paper itself. Following its publication, a curious pattern emerged: each of these eight individuals departed from Google, embarking on new ventures with other companies or establishing their own [startups](/Startup_company). This exodus, while perhaps a testament to their individual ambitions, certainly highlights the profound impact and perceived potential of the work they had accomplished.

The title itself, "Attention Is All You Need," is a sly nod to the iconic Beatles song, "[All You Need Is Love](/All_You_Need_Is_Love)." The choice of the name "Transformer" for the architecture was, according to Jakob Uszkoreit, simply a matter of aesthetic preference – he liked the sound of it. An early internal document, which hinted at the project's scope, was even titled "Transformers: Iterative Self-Attention and Processing for Various Tasks." This document reportedly featured an illustration of characters from the [Transformers](/Transformers) franchise, and the team had even christened themselves "Team Transformer." It’s a touch of whimsy that belies the groundbreaking seriousness of their endeavor.

## Methods Discussed and Introduced

The true genius of the "Attention Is All You Need" paper lies in its introduction of the Transformer architecture, which has since become the foundational blueprint for the vast majority of modern [large language models (LLMs)](/Large_language_model). A primary reason for its widespread adoption is its inherent parallelizability, a significant advantage over its sequential predecessors. This parallel processing capability allows for the acceleration of training operations on GPUs, leading to dramatically reduced training times and the feasibility of training significantly larger and more complex models.

The paper meticulously details several key mechanisms that underpin the Transformer architecture:

### Scaled Dot-Product Attention & Self-Attention

The paper champions the use of scaled dot-product attention and self-attention as a superior alternative to traditional [recurrent neural networks](/Recurrent_neural_network) or [long short-term memory](/Long_short-term_memory) (LSTMs) networks, which rely on sequential processing. This shift dramatically improves performance. The authors define scaled dot-product attention as follows:

<math display="block">
  \text{Attention}(Q,K,V):=\text{softmax}\left({\frac {Q\times K^{T}}{\sqrt {d_{k}}}}\right)\times V
</math>

Here, $Q$, $K$, and $V$ represent the query, key, and value matrices, respectively, and $d_k$ denotes the dimension of the values.

The crucial innovation here is that the Query ($Q$), Key ($K$), and Value ($V$) matrices are all derived from the same input sequence or context window. This eliminates the need for recurrent connections, thereby enabling true parallelization of the architecture. This stands in stark contrast to the original attention mechanism proposed in 2014. Furthermore, the paper introduces an additional scaling factor, the square root of the key dimension ($\sqrt{d_k}$), which was empirically found to be most effective. This scaling factor, initially set to 64 within the paper, helps to stabilize gradients during training.

In the context of machine translation, as explored in the paper, the Query and Key matrices are typically derived from the embeddings of the source language, while the Value matrix corresponds to the target language. This allows the model to weigh the importance of different parts of the source sentence when generating each word of the translated sentence.

### Multi-Head Attention

Building upon the self-attention mechanism, multi-head attention further refines the model's ability to capture complex relationships within the input sequence. In this approach, queries, keys, and values are not processed through a single attention function but are instead projected multiple times with different learned linear projections. Each of these projections, or "heads," can attend to different parts of the input sequence, effectively allowing the model to focus on different aspects of the relationships between words simultaneously.

This parallel processing of attention allows the model to capture a richer and more diverse set of contextual information. The outputs from all the attention heads are then concatenated and passed through a final linear layer, producing a refined representation of the input. This multi-perspective approach ensures that the input embeddings are updated with a more comprehensive understanding of the sequence's nuances.

### Positional Encoding

A critical challenge for the Transformer architecture, which processes input sequences in parallel rather than sequentially, is the inherent loss of positional information. To address this, the paper introduces the concept of positional encoding. Instead of relying on recurrent connections to infer word order, the Transformer embeds positional information directly into the input embeddings.

The paper proposes using sine and cosine functions of varying frequencies to encode the position of each token within the sequence. Specifically, for a position 'pos' and a dimension 'i' within the embedding vector of dimension $d_{model}$:

<math display="block">
  \text{PE}_{(\text{pos},2i)}=\sin(\text{pos}/10000^{2i/d_{\rm {model}}})
</math>
<math display="block">
  \text{PE}_{(\text{pos},2i+1)}=\cos(\text{pos}/10000^{2i/d_{\rm {model}}})
</math>

Here, $pos$ refers to the position of the word in the sequence, $i$ is the current dimension index, and $d_{model}$ is the overall dimensionality of the model's embeddings. The sine function is applied to even indices, and the cosine function to odd indices. This resulting positional encoding ($PE$) vector is then added to the corresponding word embedding. The authors specifically highlight the advantage of this sinusoidal approach: "We chose the sinusoidal version because it may allow the model to extrapolate to sequence lengths longer than the ones encountered during training." This ability to generalize to unseen sequence lengths is a significant benefit.

## Historical Context

### Predecessors

For a considerable period, sequence modeling and generation tasks were primarily handled by straightforward [recurrent neural networks](/Recurrent_neural_network) (RNNs). The [Elman network](/Elman_network), introduced in 1990, is a notable early example. While RNNs theoretically possess the capacity to propagate information across arbitrary distances within a sequence, practical limitations, most significantly the [vanishing-gradient problem](/Vanishing-gradient_problem), often hindered their ability to retain precise information from distant preceding tokens.

A pivotal advancement arrived with the development of [LSTM](/Long_short-term_memory) (1990s), a specialized type of RNN. LSTMs incorporated several innovative mechanisms designed to mitigate the vanishing gradient problem, thereby enabling more effective learning on long sequences. A key component of LSTMs was the integration of an [attention mechanism](/Attention_(machine_learning)), which utilized multiplicative units—neurons that multiply the outputs of other neurons. Neural networks employing these multiplicative units were later termed sigma-pi networks or higher-order networks. LSTMs quickly became the de facto standard for long sequence modeling, maintaining this position until the advent of the Transformer in 2017. However, even LSTMs, like most other RNNs, were fundamentally sequential in their processing, meaning they operated on one token at a time, from beginning to end, precluding parallel computation across the entire sequence.

Modern Transformers, while overcoming the sequential processing limitation, introduced a new computational challenge: their complexity scales quadratically with the size of the context window. In contrast, earlier research, such as the linearly scaling fast weight controller from 1992, explored alternative approaches. This controller learned to dynamically compute weight matrices for further processing based on the input. One of its networks featured "fast weights" or "dynamic links," a concept explored as early as 1981. In this model, a slow neural network learned via gradient descent to generate keys and values that guided the weight updates of a fast neural network responsible for generating outputs in response to queries. This mechanism was later demonstrated to be equivalent to an unnormalized linear transformer.

### Attention with Seq2Seq

The concept of encoder–decoder sequence transduction gained traction in the early 2010s. Two significant papers, published concurrently in 2014, are widely credited with popularizing this approach.

One influential model, boasting 380 million parameters, employed two [long short-term memories](/Long_short-term_memory) (LSTMs). Its architecture comprised an encoder LSTM that processed an input sequence of tokens into a vector representation, and a decoder LSTM that transformed this vector back into an output sequence of tokens. A similar 130 million-parameter model utilized [gated recurrent units](/Gated_recurrent_unit) (GRUs) instead of LSTMs. Subsequent research indicated that GRUs offered no significant performance advantage or disadvantage compared to LSTMs in seq2seq tasks.

These early seq2seq models lacked an attention mechanism. The encoded state vector was only accessible after the final word of the source text had been processed. While theoretically intended to encapsulate the entire input sentence's information, this fixed-size vector proved to be a bottleneck in practice, especially for longer sentences. The sequential processing by one recurrent network into a fixed-size output, which was then fed into another recurrent network, often resulted in a degradation of output quality as crucial information was lost. Evidence for this limitation was observed when reversing the input sentence surprisingly improved seq2seq translation performance.

To address this bottleneck problem and facilitate the processing of long-distance dependencies, the RNN search model introduced an attention mechanism to seq2seq for machine translation. The name "RNN search" aptly describes its function: it "emulates searching through a source sentence during decoding a translation." Comparative analyses of global attention (as used in RNN search) and local (sliding window) attention models for machine translation revealed that mixed attention models achieved higher quality than global attention, while local attention contributed to reduced translation times.

In 2016, [Google Translate](/Google_Translate) underwent a significant overhaul, transitioning to [Google Neural Machine Translation](/Google_Neural_Machine_Translation). This new system replaced the previous statistical machine translation approach with a seq2seq model where both the encoder and decoder consisted of eight layers of bidirectional LSTMs. This development, which took nine months to implement, significantly outperformed the decade-long development effort of the statistical method.

### Parallelizing Attention

Despite the advancements in seq2seq models with attention (including self-attention), they still inherited the inherent difficulty of parallelization from recurrent networks. This limitation hindered their ability to be effectively accelerated on GPUs. In 2016, the decomposable attention model proposed applying a self-attention mechanism to [feedforward networks](/Feedforward_neural_network), which are inherently parallelizable. This approach achieved state-of-the-art results in [textual entailment](/Textual_entailment) while utilizing an order of magnitude fewer parameters than LSTMs. Jakob Uszkoreit, one of the authors of the seminal 2017 paper, harbored a suspicion that attention alone, without recurrence, might be sufficient for language translation, leading to the paper's provocative title. This hypothesis, however, ran counter to the prevailing wisdom at the time, and even his father, [Hans Uszkoreit](/Hans_Uszkoreit), a distinguished computational linguist, expressed skepticism. In the same year, self-attention, sometimes referred to as intra-attention or intra-sentence attention, was proposed for integration within LSTMs.

In 2017, the original encoder–decoder Transformer model, with approximately 100 million parameters, was formally introduced in the "[Attention is all you need](/Attention_is_all_you_need)" paper. The primary research objective at that juncture was to enhance [seq2seq](/Seq2seq) models for [machine translation](/Machine_translation) by eliminating recurrence, thereby enabling parallel processing of all tokens, while crucially retaining the dot-product attention mechanism to preserve text processing performance. This led to the development of the multi-head attention model, which facilitated easier parallelization due to its use of independent attention heads and the absence of recurrence. Its parallelizability proved to be a critical factor in its widespread adoption within large neural networks.

## AI Boom Era

Even before the preprint of "Attention Is All You Need" was officially published in the spring of 2017, one of its co-authors had already begun experimenting with a "decoder-only" variation of the architecture. This early application was used to generate entirely fictitious Wikipedia articles, demonstrating the model's generative capabilities. The Transformer architecture has since become an integral part of numerous [generative models](/Generative_artificial_intelligence), significantly contributing to the ongoing [AI boom](/AI_boom).

In the realm of language modeling, [ELMo](/ELMo) (2018), a bi-directional LSTM, emerged as a significant development, producing contextualized [word embeddings](/Word_embedding) and building upon prior research in areas like [bag of words](/Bag-of-words_model) and [word2vec](/Word2vec). This was swiftly followed by [BERT](/BERT_(language_model)) (2018), an encoder-only Transformer model. By October 2019, Google began integrating BERT into its search query processing. In 2020, Google Translate transitioned from its RNN-encoder–RNN-decoder model to a hybrid system employing a Transformer encoder and an RNN decoder.

Beginning in 2018, OpenAI's [GPT series](/Generative_pre-trained_transformer) of decoder-only Transformers began to set new benchmarks in [natural language generation](/Natural_language_generation). The subsequent release of [ChatGPT](/ChatGPT), a chatbot built upon GPT-3, in 2022, achieved unexpected and widespread popularity, igniting a fervent surge of interest and investment in [large language models](/Large_language_model).

Since 2020, the application of Transformers has expanded beyond text to encompass other modalities. This includes the [vision transformer](/Vision_transformer), which applies Transformer principles to image recognition, as well as advancements in speech recognition, robotics, and [multimodal](/Multimodal_learning) learning. The vision transformer, in turn, has spurred new innovations in [convolutional neural networks](/Convolutional_neural_network). Generative models for images and video, such as [DALL-E](/DALL-E) (2021), [Stable Diffusion 3](/Stable_Diffusion) (2024), and [Sora](/Sora_(text-to-video_model)) (2024), utilize Transformers to analyze input data, such as text prompts. They achieve this by segmenting the input into "tokens" and then calculating the relevance between each token using self-attention, thereby enabling the model to grasp the context and intricate relationships within the data.

## Training

While the paper's principal focus was on enhancing machine translation, the authors also explored the application of the Transformer architecture to English [Constituency Parsing](/Constituent_(linguistics)). Astonishingly, the model achieved a high score on this task, even without task-specific tuning, underscoring the model's inherent versatility and promising potential for a broad spectrum of general-purpose seq2seq tasks.

### Dataset

For their English-to-German translation experiments, the model was trained on the 2014 WMT (Workshop on Statistical Machine Translation) English-German dataset. This dataset comprised nearly 4.5 million sentences, meticulously curated from TED Talks and high-quality news articles. A separate translation model was trained on the considerably larger 2014 WMT English-French dataset, which contained 36 million sentences. Both datasets were processed using byte-pair encoding, a subword tokenization technique.

### Hardware

The training of these groundbreaking models was facilitated by eight [NVIDIA P100 GPUs](/Nvidia_Tesla). The "base" models underwent training for 100,000 steps, while the larger "big" models were trained for 300,000 steps. Each step took approximately 0.4 seconds for the base models and 1.0 seconds for the big models. The total training time amounted to roughly 12 hours for the base model and 3.5 days for the big model. Remarkably, both the base and big Transformer models surpassed the state-of-the-art performance in both English-German and English-French translation tasks, all while incurring comparatively lower training costs. The estimated computational cost was a mere 0.089 petaFLOP/s–days.

### Hyperparameters and Regularization

For their 100 million-parameter Transformer model, the researchers implemented specific hyperparameter tuning strategies. The [learning rate](/Learning_rate) was initially increased linearly for the first 4,000 steps (a "warmup" period) and subsequently decreased proportionally to the inverse square root of the current step number. To prevent overfitting, dropout layers were applied to the output of each sub-layer before normalization, to the sums of embeddings, and to the positional encodings. The dropout rate was consistently set at 0.1. Additionally, label smoothing, with a value of 0.1, was employed, which the authors noted "improves accuracy and BLEU score."